Describe the {\it von K\'arm\'an effect}, and give an example from everyday life.

\underbar{file i00491}
%(END_QUESTION)





%(BEGIN_ANSWER)

Exeryday examples:

\medskip
\item{$\bullet$} A flag flapping in the breeze
\item{$\bullet$} A light pole wobbling perpendicularly to a strong wind
\item{$\bullet$} A fishing pole, dipped into the water while the boat is trolling, vibrating side-to-side
\medskip

%(END_ANSWER)





%(BEGIN_NOTES)

The {\it von K\'arm\'an effect} is the tendency for a moving fluid to fall into an oscillating vortex pattern after passing a blunt object:

$$\epsfbox{i00491x01.eps}$$

Legend has it that Theodore von K\'arm\'an noted this effect while fishing in Transylvania.  Honestly, I couldn't make up this kind of stuff if I tried.  Source: {\it Instrument Engineers' Handbook, Fourth Edition, B\'ela Lipt\'ak (editor)}, page 167.

